{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.68,0.01,0.19,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52099"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1729"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37417"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1189"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52099"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of nausea and lower abdominal pain associated with urinary frequency. She has regular 28-day menstrual cycles, and her last period was just over four weeks ago. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 112/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. She is tender in the right iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transvaginal ultrasound","Urinary beta-HCG","Full blood count","Serum beta-HCG","Urinalysis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 16-year-old girl with symptoms that could be consistent with several conditions, including ectopic pregnancy, urinary tract infection, appendicitis, or ovarian pathology. Given her age and sexual maturity, pregnancy-related complications must be considered and ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary beta-HCG\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation. It is a rapid, non-invasive, and highly sensitive test that can quickly determine if the patient is pregnant. This information is crucial for guiding further management and investigations. A positive result would raise suspicion for ectopic pregnancy given the patient\u0027s symptoms and would prompt immediate further evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is an important investigation in the evaluation of suspected ectopic pregnancy. However, it should not be performed before confirming pregnancy status with a beta-HCG test. Additionally, in a 16-year-old patient who may not be sexually active, a less invasive approach should be considered first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood count\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful investigation in many acute presentations, including suspected infection or inflammation. While it would likely be performed as part of the workup, it is not the most urgent or informative test in this scenario where pregnancy status needs to be determined first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum beta-HCG\u003C/strong\u003E is more sensitive than urinary tests and can provide quantitative results. However, it takes longer to process and is not necessary as the initial test. If the urinary test is positive or if there is high clinical suspicion despite a negative urine test, a serum beta-HCG would then be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinalysis\u003C/strong\u003E can help diagnose urinary tract infections, which could explain some of the patient\u0027s symptoms. However, given the possibility of pregnancy-related complications, determining pregnancy status takes precedence over investigating for UTI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, a urinary beta-HCG test is the most appropriate next step as it quickly provides crucial information that will guide further management and investigations in this patient with abdominal pain and delayed menses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ectopic pregnancy should always be considered in women of child-bearing age who present with sudden onset lower abdominal pain.","A urinary beta-HCG test is a rapid, sensitive, and non-invasive first-line investigation for suspected pregnancy in the emergency setting.","Clinical assessment and pregnancy testing should precede imaging studies in young women with abdominal pain."],"references":["Schuur JD, Tibbetts SA, Pines JM. Pregnancy testing in women of reproductive age in US emergency departments, 2002 to 2006: assessment of a national quality measure. Ann Emerg Med 2010;55:449\u201357","Dessie A, Steele D, Liu AR, Amanullah S, Constantine E. Point-of-Care Ultrasound Assessment of Bladder Fullness for Female Patients Awaiting Radiology-Performed Transabdominal Pelvic Ultrasound in a Pediatric Emergency Department: A Randomized Controlled Trial. Ann Emerg Med. 2018 Nov;72(5):571-580. doi: 10.1016/j.annemergmed.2018.04.010. Epub 2018 Jul 3. PMID: 29980460.","Samuels-Kalow M, Mollen C. ACUTE PELVIC PAIN IN THE ADOLESCENT: A CASE REPORT. Clin Pediatr Emerg Med. 2015 Jun 1;16(2):119-124. doi: 10.1016/j.cpem.2015.04.005. PMID: 26273230; PMCID: PMC4528383."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37417"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37417"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T13:20:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T08:56:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1729"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52099"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of t